Paley also, in the Preface to his Morol Philosophy, censuros Grotius for the profusion of his classical quota- tions; an objection of which I have already spoken, and which I have here tried to remedy; and for the forensic cast of his writings. Thetin the work of Grotius we see everywhere traces of the juristical training of his· mind, is not to be denicd; hut it may be much doubted whether this is a disadvantagc ;—whether this legal discipline of the intellect have not given a precision to his divisions and reasonings which they would not have· had without the habits so formed. Certainly a jurist would find, in Paley himself, great reason to complain that questions of morality and of law are mingled together in a very con· fused and arbitrary manner.
